            <RichTextBlock FontFamily="Segoe UI" FontSize="16" Foreground="{StaticResource ApplicationForegroundThemeBrush}">
                <Paragraph>Text selection is optimized for touch in Windows Store Apps. Gestures for selection creation, manipulation, and commanding (such as cut, copy, paste) are all touch-centric.
                    <LineBreak/>
                </Paragraph>
                <Paragraph>
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Readonly text" />
                    <Run Text=" (in this example TextBlock)" />
                </Paragraph>
                <Paragraph>Tapping on a word selects it. Once a selection has been made, selection grippers are shown on either end of the selection. These grippers respond to touch and can be dragged around the text control to extend the selection forwards and backwards.
                    <LineBreak/>
                </Paragraph>
                <Paragraph>Static text controls have default context menus which place actions, like copy, at your finger tips. Try tapping or pressing and holding and then lifting your finger on selected text or a selection gripper. Up pops a context menu!
                    <LineBreak/>
                </Paragraph>
                <Paragraph>
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Editable text" />
                    <Run Text=" (in this example TextBox)" />
                </Paragraph>
                <Paragraph>Tapping on a word places the caret at the beginning or end of the word depending on which side is closer to the tap point. Once the caret has been placed, a gripper is shown under the caret. This grippers responds to touch and can be dragged around. As you drag the caret gripper, a selection is created in the direction of the gesture. Now a selection is present which responds to touch the same way as a selection in readonly text. Try invoking the context menu in editable text and notice that you have more commands to choose from.
                    <LineBreak/>
                </Paragraph>
            </RichTextBlock>
        </Grid>

